Welcome to JQMCBP XVI! Good to be back again, burning the midnight oil to bring you the most important email you'll receive all Friday morning between midnight and 2am.

Firstly, quite literally, I am the proud father of Carson Moxie Klaas, who sits on top of the heap in 1st place after the first sixteen games, tied with ALL CAPS JACOB BENSON of Colorado. I let her know right before bedtime that she was tied for 1st place (and this was before her prophetic Harvard pick rolled in late, shedding most of those she was tied with). She was so excited she let out a girlish scream (more on girlish screams in the mailbag below). JQMCBP history shows that the first day rabbits usually fall back to the pack as the tournament progresses, but for now she's top of the class. And kudos to you too JACOB BENSON, but DO STOP SHOUTING I CAN TOTALLY HEAR YOU.

My whole family entered this year, and when I was reading the bracket to my other daughter Piper I was giving her the mascots for each team. Since I've been doing this tournament for an eternity I've memorized most of these (though ousted already, love those Akron Zips). But when I came to Belmont I was stuck so I just said with a chuckle "The Belmont Stakes". This went over 1st grader Piper's head, but as she is wont to do she took it in a different direction and started calling all of the teams "Steaks". Kansas Steaks, North Carolina Steaks, etc. So anyway, I end up looking up the Belmont mascot and it's the Bruins. Which of course makes total sense because Belmont is in Nashville, and that city is just crawling with bears.

For the rookies:
What I do is send out email updates (personalized just for your entry!) several times during the course of the tournament. I go on and on and on over seemingly meaningless minutia. It might seem meaningless but...well okay, it's meaningless. But we'll have fun, or your money back.*

In addition to the emails, there's lots of important, vital resources available with your web browser. Check out the links at the bottom of the email or head to http://benklaas.com/jqmcbp/leaderboard.cgi as a jumping off point.

* Refund applications need to be filed in triplicate and mailed to the Johnny Quest Memorial Candy Bar Pool Customer Service Department, care of its Parent Corporation, Slaptronics Personal Massage Therapy and Self Help Video Distribution Corporation of Netherland Antilles (nasdaq:SPMTSHVDCNA). Or you could contact your congressperson, which will give you a similar outcome.

One technical item of business: I've spent years and years rejiggering my home brew email program to get around the myriad spam filters, and this year has proven to finally hit the breaking point where I think more than half of my emails are going directly to people's spam folder. So, I talked to my old pal Lucky the Chimp, who is a seasoned expert in the sending of bulk email. Lucky doesn't call it spam but instead "targeted tomfoolery". Regardless, Lucky's service of choice is, I might have guessed it, MailChimp (I am not making this up). So I'm giving a shot at sending this year's emails through the MailChimp service in hopes of hitting more inboxes and less junk folders.

Because of using MailChimp the links you see in the email will be long and ugly but they will correclty redirect to where I'm pointing you. Scouts honor, no shenanigans!

ALSO, even worse, MailChimp will not allow me to send multiple emails to the same address. So if you signed up several brackets on one email address, you will not be getting a personalized email for each entry, just one. How about we call this a "feature" and call an end to the tech talk.

Now let's get on with it!
